Jupyter Notebook presentation¶

Robert Beck, 03/14/2018¶

Why use Jupyter?¶

Integrated environment for all phases of research¶

  • Text: project description, notes, references, conclusions
  • Equations via LaTeX, tables
  • Data processing
  • Computations
  • Visualization
  • Straightforward to convert into research paper
  • Easy to save, share and reproduce work
  • Growing popularity

Architecture¶

  • Local or remote notebook server
  • Purely web interface, accessible from any browser
    • Password/token authentication
  • Supports a wide variety of kernels to perform computations
    • Python, R
    • Matlab/Octave
    • IDL
    • Mathematica
    • C/C++, Fortran
    • C#, Java
    • Haskell
  • Notebook file (.ipynb) containing all text/code/images
    • Can be exported to pdf/html for sharing

"Standard" setup - Python¶

  • Numpy/Pandas/Python for datafile manipulation
  • Numpy/Scipy for scientific computation
  • Matplotlib for visualization

Installation¶

https://www.anaconda.com/download/ for Win/Linux/Mac, Python+Jupyter+common packages

Alternative with existing Python installation: $pip install jupyter

Additional packages¶

$conda install package_name

$pip install package_name

Running the server¶

$jupyter notebook

Connecting to it from a browser¶

http://localhost:8888 for a standard local server, otherwise address:port

Provide password/token, access directory tree and start running notebooks

Files are only accessible in the subdirectories of where the notebook server was started!

Notebook structure¶

  • Made up of cells
    • Markdown cells contain formatted text, images, tables
    • Code cells contain code, runnable in the given language kernel
  • Read-evaluate-print loop (REPL), i.e. interactive shell ran piecewise
    • Output of variables, figures, etc.

Markdown examples¶

It is generally possible to use Markdown and HTML language features in Markdown cells, such as italic, bold or both.

  • We already saw
  • dotted lists

  2. unsurprisingly

Levels¶

Of highlighted headers¶

When you need to include equations, you can do it inline to say $E=mc^2$ or $d\tau=dt \, / \, a\left(t\right)$ in LaTeX. Or you can have them longer and centered:

$$ \frac{\Delta T}{T} = - \frac{2}{c^2} \int_{\tau_0}^{\tau_{z=9}} d\tau \frac{\partial\Phi\left(\vec{r}(\tau),\tau\right)}{\partial\tau}$$

$$\frac{\partial\Phi\left(\vec{k},\tau\right)}{\partial\tau} = a \dot{\Phi} = a \frac{3}{2}\left(\frac{H_0}{k}\right)^2 \Omega_m \frac{1}{a} \left[\frac{\dot{a}}{a} \delta\left(\vec{k},t\right)\left( 1-\beta(t)\right)\right] =\frac{3}{2}\left(\frac{H_0}{k}\right)^2 \Omega_m \left[\frac{\dot{a}}{a} \delta\left(\vec{k},t\right)\left( 1-\beta(t)\right)\right] $$

Sample code (unrunnable) can also be put here, even with syntax highlighting for a given language:

x=np.linspace(-pi,pi,1000)
y=list(cos(x))

There are even response-like indentations. C code below.

double x=0.0;
for (int i=0; i<5; ++i){
   x+=sqrt(i);
}

There can be more levels of indentations.

Code example¶

This short line will import the most common numpy and matplotlib modules into the namespace for convenience. Numpy is np, matplotlib is plt.

In [7]:
%pylab inline

Populating the interactive namespace from numpy and matplotlib
In [8]:
a=5+2
a
Out[8]:
7
In [9]:
[x**2 for x in range(a)]
Out[9]:
[0, 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36]

You can write and execute Python code in such fields. Objects/variables will stay in memory as long as the kernel isn't stopped/doesn't crash. (That is, unless they are explicitly deleted, or have no more references to them and are garbage collected.)

The documentation of a function can be opened within the notebook with the ? symbol:

?np.random.normal

 # %load data/LLR.py
import math
import numpy as np
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor

def localLinearRegression(trainingCoordinates, trainingResponses, testCoordinates, neighborNumber, trainingWeights=None):
    
    sampleNumber = testCoordinates.shape[0]
    dim=testCoordinates.shape[1]

    if trainingWeights is None:
        trainingWeights=np.ones(trainingCoordinates.shape[0])

    testResponses = np.zeros(sampleNumber)

    knnreg = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=neighborNumber, weights='uniform', algorithm='kd_tree', leaf_size=40, p=2)
    knnreg.fit(trainingCoordinates, trainingResponses)

    for sample in range(0, sampleNumber):
        # find kNN

        [dist, ni] = knnreg.kneighbors(testCoordinates[sample,:].reshape(1,-1), neighborNumber)

        X=np.concatenate((np.ones(neighborNumber).reshape(-1,1),trainingCoordinates[ni.squeeze(),:]),axis=1)
        y=trainingResponses[ni.squeeze()]
        w=np.diag(trainingWeights[ni.squeeze()])


        rhs=np.zeros(dim+1)
        
        rhs=y.dot(w.dot(X))
        #for m in range(0, dim+1):
        #    for k in range(0,neighborNumber):
        #        rhs[m]+=X[k,m]*y[k]*w[k]

        lhs=np.zeros((dim+1,dim+1))
        
        lhs=(X.T).dot(w.dot(X))
        #for m in range(0,dim+1):
        #    for n in range(0,dim+1):
        #        for k in range(0,neighborNumber):
        #            lhs[m,n]+=X[k,m]*X[k,n]*w[k]

        try:
            coefficients = np.linalg.solve(lhs, rhs)
        except:
            break

        testResponses[sample]=(np.concatenate((np.ones(1),testCoordinates[sample,:]),axis=0).reshape(1,-1)).dot(coefficients.reshape(-1,1))

    return testResponses,coefficients,ni

from scipy import integrate

sims=['BR','LCDM','EdS']
simColors=['blue','red','green']
simLabels=['AvERA','$\\Lambda$CDM','EdS']

times=[]
scaleFactors=[]
hubbleFactors=[]

snapshotNames=[]

for sim in sims:
    globalSimParams=np.genfromtxt('data/timeCurve_'+sim+'.txt',dtype='str')
    
    times.append(np.array([float(f) for f in globalSimParams[:,0]]))
    scaleFactors.append(np.array([float(f) for f in globalSimParams[:,1]]))
    hubbleFactors.append(np.array([float(f) for f in globalSimParams[:,3]]))
    
    snapshotNames.append(globalSimParams[:,2])
    
    
taus=[]
    
for i in range(len(sims)):
    
    taus.append(3*times[i][0]/scaleFactors[i][0]+integrate.cumtrapz(1.0/scaleFactors[i],times[i],initial=0))

def plotLinearRegression(xValues, yValues, xParam=0.0, kParam=50):
    
    #Plot the figure first
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,16))
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)

    ax1.set_xlabel('$x$', fontsize=40)
    ax1.set_ylabel('$y$', fontsize=40)
    ax1.tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=32, pad=14)

    ax1.set_ylim(-1.5,1.5)
    ax1.set_xlim(0,2.2*pi)
    
    points = ax1.plot(xCoord[:,0], yCoord, 'bo')
    
    #Do the linear regression
    
    xParam=np.array(xParam).reshape([1,1])

    [estimate, param, neighborIDs]=localLinearRegression(xValues,
                                                         yValues,
                                                         xParam,
                                                         kParam)

    xFit=xCoord
    yFit=param[0]+xFit*param[1]
    
    #Plot the estimates
    
    fitLine = ax1.plot(xFit, yFit, 'r-', linewidth=3)
    neighborPoints = ax1.plot(xValues[neighborIDs,0], yValues[neighborIDs], 'ro', linewidth=3, markersize=10)
    fitPoint = ax1.plot(xParam, estimate, 'ko', linewidth=3, markersize=15)
    
    return

from matplotlib.animation import FuncAnimation

frameNum=15

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,16))
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(111)

ax1.set_xlabel('$x$', fontsize=40)
ax1.set_ylabel('$y$', fontsize=40)
ax1.tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=32, pad=14)

ax1.set_ylim(-1.5,1.5)
ax1.set_xlim(0,2.2*pi)

i=0
points = ax1.plot(xCoord[:,0], yCoord, 'bo')

def update(i):
    
    test=np.empty((1,1))
    test[0,0]=i*2.2*pi/frameNum

    [estimate, param, neighborIDs] = localLinearRegression(xCoord, yCoord, test, 50)
    
    xs=np.arange(0,2.2*pi+1e-6,2.2*pi/(pointNum-1))
    ys=param[0]+xs*param[1]
    
    while (len(ax1.lines)>1):
        ax1.lines.pop()
    
    fitLine = ax1.plot(xs, ys, 'r-', linewidth=3)
    neighborPoints = ax1.plot(xCoord[neighborIDs,0], yCoord[neighborIDs], 'ro', linewidth=3, markersize=10)
    fitPoint = ax1.plot(test[0,0], estimate, 'ko', linewidth=3, markersize=15)
    
    return ax1

# FuncAnimation will call the 'update' function for each frame; here
# animating over frameNum frames, with an interval of 300ms between frames.
anim = FuncAnimation(fig, update, frames=range(frameNum), interval=300)


anim.save('fig/LLRimag.gif', dpi=80, writer='imagemagick')

Programming-debugging example¶

Say I want to find similar points (e.g. within 0.2 in x) that satisfy a criterion (e.g. 70% are well-measured)

In [40]:
goodProbability=0.7
xSearchRange=0.2

goodPoints=np.random.uniform(size=len(xCoord))<goodProbability

similarIDs=[]

for i in range(len(xCoord)):
    
    closePointIDs=np.where(abs(xCoord-xCoord[i])<xSearchRange)
    
    #goodPoints[closePointIDs] -> these are the True/False (good/bad) values for each close object
    
    similarIDs.append(closePointIDs[goodPoints[closePointIDs]])
    #similarIDs.append(closePointIDs[0][goodPoints[closePointIDs[0]]])
